    <statement><p>The pie chart represents a school<rsq/>s student population.</p>
<!-- PTX:WARNING: PGML wanted to center align here. -->
<image xmlns:pi="http://pretextbook.org/2020/pretext/internal" pi:generated="webwork/images/section-fractions-and-fraction-arithmetic-9-3-8-image-1.png" width="83%"/>
<p>Together, white and black students make up <fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/> of the school<rsq/>s population.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{19}{30}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>By the pie chart, the school has <m>{{\frac{1}{3}}}</m> white students, and <m>{{\frac{3}{10}}}</m> black students.</p>
<p>We will use addition to find the total portion of white and black students at this school.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   \amp \phantom{{}=}{{\frac{1}{3}}}+{{\frac{3}{10}}} \\
   \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 10}{3 \cdot 10} + \frac{3 \cdot 10}{10 \cdot 10} \\
   \amp = \frac{10}{30} + \frac{9}{30} \\
   \amp = \frac{10+9}{30} \\
   \amp = \frac{19}{30} \\ 
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Together, white and black students make up <m>{{\frac{19}{30}}}</m> of the school<rsq/>s population.</p>
</solution>
